text.tspan: n=5, k=5. Kaufman says this is the one possible wiring
diagram of the 'Grand Ensemble'. That there is
just one possible diagram means that a neat
table can be drawn, in for which for any gene a-e,
input i is always from gene a (red), input ii is always
from b (blue), iii from c (green) etc. However, the inputs
can still be swapped around. Compare this connectivity with
the connectivity defined in the Attractor Scaffolding paper. The only
difference is the defintition of the inputs to which each connection is wired.
n=5, k=4. How to remove the one input? Answer: Have
to choose. There are many possibilities. The most obvious
k=n-1 is for self to not influence its own future state. And here,
we see that the relationship between input index and the
originating gene state (i.e. the colour) is lost.
Alternatively, keep the input index to originating state relationship, to force
i=input red, ii=input yellow etc. The resulting system has an input-only
relationship for gene e; the value of gene e is not able to influence the
rest of the network. This is 'canalyzing for gene e' because the value of e
cannot affect the rest of the network's outcome.
Another approach is to keep all five inputs available, but mark some as 'ignored'.
This way, you have a 5 col input/output table, but you have to make 5 copies of
the table, with each copy showing the inputs from the point of view of genes a-e.
I like this approach - it makes it obvious how the code could configure the wiring; by
randomly, or sequentially marking inputs to be ignored.
Sequential case for k=n-1 as in D. For k=n-2:
I'd ignore a(i,ii), b(ii,iii), c(iii,iv), d(iv,v), e(v,i).
a(i,ii,iii), b(ii,iii,iv), c(iii,iv,v), d(iv,v,i), e(v,i,ii). See GeneNet::setup_inputs().
So, final question: Do we use A for the connectivity wiring or the original pattern as in
the paper. Now probably the latter. In that case the sequential input ignorance is:
k=n-1: a(i), b(i), c(i), d(i), d(i), e(i)
